content.description: Overhanging offset thin hands to fingers crack which finishes with a couple exciting slab moves.  Crux is turning the overhanging bulge.
content.protection: Small cams and nuts (around blue tcu sizes)
content.location: East side of the Grand Central Station boulder.

content.description: Another perfect finger crack on the backside of the GCStation boulder.  A little too short otherwise this would have more stars.
content.protection: Finger sized nuts and cams for lead or TR
content.location: On the South west side of the Grand Central Station boulder.  Faces west.

content.description:
Start with a great sidepull on large grained but good quality rock. Make moves to the lip and press the tough mantle. Couple of slab moves at the top can go direct or escape slightly to the left.

Great problem at Woodson! It's relatively localized area makes it likely it has done before - if anyone has an information I would love to hear about it. These may be route 125 (pg 44) in Dave Kennedy and Chris Hubbard's San Diego County Guidebook...
content.location: From Grand Central Station, walk towards and around Manuel's Climb. From there go traverse bushes/rocks to get to this problem

content.description: Perfect fingers in a left facing corner.  Good climb but a little short.
content.protection: Finger sized cams and nuts for lead or TR
content.location: Facing west on the main Grand Central Station boulder.

content.description: Slab/face climbing on nicely featured rock. There is a wide dike up the middle that provides a lot of holds but you can pretty much climb all over this face, including the seam on the right side of the face. As is the case with many Woodson climbs, if only it was longer...
content.protection: 1 bolt on top and a #1 camalot fits in the horizontal crack just under the lip. The landing is good enough to make this a boulder problem, as long as you don't land on the yucca.
content.location: Just north of the GSS boulder. Hard to miss.
